  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2700242788" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2700242788" />
    <a title="Alex" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/63874957-alex"><img alt="Alex" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1574597085p2/63874957.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2700242788?book_show_action=true">Aug 15, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alex" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alex" href="/user/show/63874957-alex">Alex</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2700242788" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4024639315023220033">Magnificent. Simply magnificent. I spent nearly three months reading this. That&apos;s not abnormal for a book of this length since I have several going at any given time, but with these long ones there is often a moment when I face what I call the Swamp of Despair. It&apos;s that lull in the middle of a book when the novelty of breaking port has worn off and the destination is still a distant shore. This time the slog never came. Nearly 700 pages in, I read a chapter that felt as fresh as the first—all s</span>
  <span id="freeText4024639315023220033" style="display:none">Magnificent. Simply magnificent. I spent nearly three months reading this. That's not abnormal for a book of this length since I have several going at any given time, but with these long ones there is often a moment when I face what I call the Swamp of Despair. It's that lull in the middle of a book when the novelty of breaking port has worn off and the destination is still a distant shore. This time the slog never came. Nearly 700 pages in, I read a chapter that felt as fresh as the first—all sense of where I was in the book and how long I had been reading it disappeared. This might be in part because George's life lends itself to the perfect structure for a biography, slicing neatly into three phases—his military years, his estate years, his political years—but surely it's a testament to Chernow's abilities as a writer.<br /><br />Something that I hadn't truly appreciated before reading this was that George wasn't just the first President, <i>he invented the presidency</i>. Much of the pageantry of the presidential office is thanks to George—things like the Inauguration Ceremony, or the State of the Union Address. And George did those things that way because, well, that's the way he decided to do them. It wasn't just things of decorum either. There were decisions that to be made for which there was no precedent. <i>Who has power here, Congress or the President? </i> George made a decision. Now there was a precedent. Many of those judgments persist as American policy and procedure today.<br /><br />One thing I admired about Chernow is that he kept the camera interminably trained on George. In a period of epoch-shaping events and colossus personalities, it would be easy to lose focus. Chernow never does. This is a book <i>about George</i>, and perhaps the best thing I can say about it is that I came away completely unsure of who George was as a person. His character and contributions to world history are known (relatively well) and rightly revered. He's been lionized to a point that it seems it would be sacrilege to merely question, let alone criticize, him or his legacy in even the smallest regard. But he was a hard man. He was temperamental and often gave vent to his temperaments. He exercised corporal punishment on soldiers and slaves, and verbal punishment on political antagonists and allies alike. He was unscrupulous in business dealings, and despite the comportment of humble servitude fronted by a charming aura of stoicism, I cannot shake the thought that much of his suave self-abasement in the political arena was actually a masterclass in ruthless self-advancement by a politically ambitious politician supremely gifted in the art of politics.<br /><br />And that is why my ambivalence about George is a compliment to Chernow. He's fair. He presents both sides of his subject. He clearly holds a favorable opinion of George, but he doesn't foist it upon us. (The one area where he made a hard sell was in trying to convince of George's moral repulsion to slavery. Despite Chernow's best efforts to portray George as internally conflicted over the issue, I found it difficult to buy given his sustained pattern of behavior that carried all the way through the end of his life. But again, to Chernow's credit, he doesn't hide that behavior.) These contradictions are all part of George's mystique. He was an enigma to those in his day. He was beloved by many. He was also decried by many (and in a definitively sad note, his sharp words would sever relationships with many once-close friends—Jefferson, Madison, Knox, Adams). If a modern author were to write a biography that leaves the impression of a clear-cut figure, it would smack of inauthenticity. Not so here. I'm baffled by George, therefore I know him.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4024639315023220033" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


