<div id="review_2458631065" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2458631065" />
    <a title="Erik Graff" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/974210-erik-graff"><img alt="Erik Graff" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1299888977p2/974210.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2458631065?book_show_action=true">Jul 15, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Erik Graff" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Erik Graff" href="/user/show/974210-erik-graff">Erik Graff</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">US citizens</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Erik by: </span>
      no one
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/974210-erik-graff?shelf=biography">biography</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2458631065" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15156643459666576728">This was my first adult biography of George Washington, serving to tie together the tidbits from other mature histories about the period of his life, exposing the actual man as opposed to the icon we learned about in elementary school. What I learned was illuminating as well as disappointing.<br/><br/>Unlike most presidents, it appears that Washington was technically faithful to his wife. Indeed, he was, by his own lights, quite proper and generally recognized as such. He was, however, throughout his life</span>
  <span id="freeText15156643459666576728" style="display:none">This was my first adult biography of George Washington, serving to tie together the tidbits from other mature histories about the period of his life, exposing the actual man as opposed to the icon we learned about in elementary school. What I learned was illuminating as well as disappointing.<br /><br />Unlike most presidents, it appears that Washington was technically faithful to his wife. Indeed, he was, by his own lights, quite proper and generally recognized as such. He was, however, throughout his life, a major slaveholder during a period when many opposed the institution and, feeling some guilt about the practice, he did will the emancipation of his personal slaves upon his death. Still, what counted more than conscience for him may have been appearances, appearances 'proper' to a patrician landowner and well behaved slaves were valuable. Further, both as a slaveholder and as a military commander, he expected those beneath himself to comport themselves properly, exacting harsh punishments such as whipping for soldiers who drank to excess or swore and execution for deserters. Uncooperative slaves, being more valuable than conscripts, he sold off to island plantations to the south. Runaways he had pursued.<br /><br />The virtues of Washington exemplified the values of his time as he was almost universally revered. He was, to virtually all appearances, courageous, responsible, steady, self-controlled, self-contained, dependable--a man with a fine sense of duty: duty to family and to the federal state he helped to create and sustain during its early decades. He even had a sense of duty, of responsibilities towards his hundreds of slaves, duties such as not separating families--except, of course, when it was too financially difficult to keep them together. Washington was not good with money. Keeping up appearances was expensive.<br /><br />Chernow, to his credit, appears to present the reader with the whole man. While he clearly admires Washington, he recognizes many of his flaws, especially as regards slavery, a topic broached repeatedly and often at length.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15156643459666576728" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


