    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_125218574" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/125218574" />
    <a title="Tony" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/33771-tony"><img alt="Tony" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1292869016p2/33771.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/125218574?book_show_action=true">Oct 07, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tony" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tony" href="/user/show/33771-tony">Tony</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/33771-tony?shelf=top-10-2010">top-10-2010</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/33771-tony?shelf=presidents">presidents</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer125218574" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7259886422700141914">How to breathe life into this man, already eulogized, mythologized, stamped on currency and sculpted into marble? Washington didn&apos;t help by being so guarded and so careful with his public image. His wife didn&apos;t help by burning their correspondence. So, historians have suffered (or invented).<br/><br/>Chernow has succeeded, and convincingly. He does it by looking at Washington in relation to others. Thus, we see Washington the pragmatic yet loving husband. So, he married for money. So what? He was faithful</span>
  <span id="freeText7259886422700141914" style="display:none">How to breathe life into this man, already eulogized, mythologized, stamped on currency and sculpted into marble? Washington didn't help by being so guarded and so careful with his public image. His wife didn't help by burning their correspondence. So, historians have suffered (or invented).<br /><br />Chernow has succeeded, and convincingly. He does it by looking at Washington in relation to others. Thus, we see Washington the pragmatic yet loving husband. So, he married for money. So what? He was faithful. (Chernow <i>does</i> have an unfortunate preoccupation with the sex lives of his subjects). And there existed a tenderness and need.<br /><br />Childless, Washington nevertheless seemed to relish an avuncular role with younger family members and with ascendant talents like Hamilton.<br /><br />Washington's response, or lack of response, to the betrayals of Jefferson, Madison and Monroe and to the pettiness of Adams, shows not just a political delicacy but a moral courage of being <i>the better man</i>. Just so you know, Chernow has not one good word to say about Jefferson -- <i>not one</i>. I'm okay with that. And Washington's relationship with Henry Knox is revealing; and not just historically, but about how hard and even unfair life can be when you truly enjoy and admire someone and still have to make decisions that shatter a friendship.<br /><br />Chernow does spend a bit too much time telling us how many dances Washington did at numerous parties and there was some repetition. Yet, small details proved illuminating. Like Washington's teeth. We all know about Washington's dental problems, but Chernow lets us see them in a social context: how an already circumspect man just didn't like to speak in public because of dental pain and loose dentures. Chernow made the inconvenience very real.<br /><br />One of the best, recurring themes of the book is Washington's struggle with slavery. Better than most, Washington still never fully grasped what the lack of freedom meant. His decision to free <i>his</i> slaves was well-told, as well as Martha's decision to free <i>hers</i> for entirely different reasons. It also gave Chernow another chance to compare Jefferson unfavorably. <br /><br />Beyond the 'biography' though, Chernow, in <i>Washington: A Life</i>, made me think of the American Revolution in a wholly new way. Most revolutions, historically and globally, are spawned by the masses: the underprivileged, the persecuted, the rabble. Men arise when there is nothing left to do and death doesn't matter. The American Revolution was different, Chernow teaches. The rebels were the landowners, the aristocrats, shop-owners and political leaders. This was a revolution from the top down. So when the rebels won, they created a government and an economic system that was entirely different from any before. It was neither monarchist nor socialist, but one that encouraged individual freedom. What a great idea. Yet, it all could have folded early from personal and sectional interests, from foreign mischief and sneaky, scheming rivals, but for one great man.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7259886422700141914" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

